 to environmental instability and why we resist changing our destructive habits. Ultimately, Brontë's lifelong engagement with the nonhuman world offers five powerful strategies for coping with ecological crises: to witness destruction carefully, to write about it unflinchingly, to apply those experiences by questioning and redefining toxic definitions of the human, and to mourn the dead, all without forgetting to tend the living.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHuman ecology in literature. 0aNature in literature. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Environmental Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aLiterature : English Literature. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Nineteenth-Century Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Women Authors.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2020z978311149149340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438479880423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438479880/original  a978-3-11-149149-3  SUNY Press eBook Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles